-- ============================================================================
-- Quiz Seed: Romans — Part 2 (Chapters 9–16)
-- 3 difficulties × 8 chapters = 128 total questions
--   kids:   3 per chapter  = 24
--   teens:  5 per chapter  = 40
--   adults: 8 per chapter  = 64
-- ============================================================================

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 9–12 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 9 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 9, 'kids', 1, 'How much did Paul care about his fellow Israelites?', 'So much that he wished he could be cut off from Christ for their sake', 'He did not care about them', 'He only cared a little', 'He wanted them to be punished', 'a', 'Romans 9:3 — "For I could wish that myself were accursed from Christ for my brethren, my kinsmen according to the flesh."'),
('Romans', 9, 'kids', 2, 'Does God have the right to do whatever He wants, like a potter with clay?', 'Yes, the potter has power over the clay to make what he chooses', 'No, the clay tells the potter what to do', 'The potter and clay are equal', 'The clay has more power than the potter', 'a', 'Romans 9:21 — "Hath not the potter power over the clay, of the same lump to make one vessel unto honour, and another unto dishonour?"'),
('Romans', 9, 'kids', 3, 'What did God say about Jacob and Esau before they were born?', 'The elder shall serve the younger', 'The younger shall serve the elder', 'Both shall be kings', 'Neither shall serve the other', 'a', 'Romans 9:12 — "It was said unto her, The elder shall serve the younger."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 9, 'teens', 1, 'What special privileges did Israel receive from God?', 'The adoption, the glory, the covenants, the giving of the law, the service of God, and the promises', 'Only the law and nothing else', 'No special privileges at all', 'Only material blessings', 'a', 'Romans 9:4 — "Who are Israelites; to whom pertaineth the adoption, and the glory, and the covenants, and the giving of the law, and the service of God, and the promises."'),
('Romans', 9, 'teens', 2, 'What principle does God''s choice of Jacob over Esau illustrate?', 'God''s sovereign election — His purpose stands not of works but of Him that calleth', 'That Jacob was morally better than Esau', 'That older children are less important', 'That twins should always be separated', 'a', 'Romans 9:11 — "That the purpose of God according to election might stand, not of works, but of him that calleth."'),
('Romans', 9, 'teens', 3, 'What does God say to Moses about mercy?', 'I will have mercy on whom I will have mercy, and I will have compassion on whom I will have compassion', 'I will have mercy only on Israel', 'Mercy is given based on good works', 'Everyone automatically receives mercy', 'a', 'Romans 9:15 — "For he saith to Moses, I will have mercy on whom I will have mercy, and I will have compassion on whom I will have compassion."'),
('Romans', 9, 'teens', 4, 'What does Paul say about God raising up Pharaoh?', 'God raised him up to show His power in him and that His name might be declared throughout all the earth', 'Pharaoh rose to power by accident', 'God had no involvement with Pharaoh', 'Pharaoh deserved his position', 'a', 'Romans 9:17 — "For the scripture saith unto Pharaoh, Even for this same purpose have I raised thee up, that I might shew my power in thee, and that my name might be declared throughout all the earth."'),
('Romans', 9, 'teens', 5, 'What stumbling stone did Israel stumble over?', 'Christ — they sought righteousness by works of the law instead of by faith', 'A literal stone in the road', 'The temple steps', 'The law of Moses', 'a', 'Romans 9:32-33 — "They stumbled at that stumblingstone; As it is written, Behold, I lay in Sion a stumblingstone and rock of offence."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 1, 'How does Paul''s statement about wishing himself accursed (anathema) demonstrate his pastoral heart?', 'Paul would exchange his own salvation for Israel''s — echoing Moses'' similar plea (Exodus 32:32), showing the depth of apostolic love for his people', 'Paul was being hyperbolic and insincere', 'Paul regretted becoming a Christian', 'Paul wanted to return to Judaism', 'a', 'Romans 9:3 — "For I could wish that myself were accursed from Christ for my brethren, my kinsmen according to the flesh." This echoes Moses'' plea in Exodus 32:32.'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 2, 'What does Paul mean by "not all Israel are of Israel" in verse 6?', 'Physical descent from Abraham does not guarantee membership in the true spiritual Israel — God''s promise applies to the children of promise, not merely of the flesh', 'All ethnic Israelites are saved', 'Israel as a nation has been replaced', 'Only half of Israel is truly Israel', 'a', 'Romans 9:6-8 — "They are not all Israel, which are of Israel: Neither, because they are the seed of Abraham, are they all children: but, In Isaac shall thy seed be called."'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 3, 'How does Paul respond to the objection "Is there unrighteousness with God?"', 'God forbid — Paul appeals to God''s sovereign right to show mercy or harden as He wills, quoting Exodus 33:19 and Exodus 9:16', 'He admits there may be some unfairness', 'He changes the subject', 'He says the question is irrelevant', 'a', 'Romans 9:14-17 — "Is there unrighteousness with God? God forbid. For he saith to Moses, I will have mercy on whom I will have mercy."'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 4, 'What does the potter-clay analogy teach about God''s sovereignty?', 'God as Creator has absolute right over His creation — to make vessels of honour or dishonour from the same lump, displaying both His wrath and His mercy', 'God is arbitrary and uncaring', 'Humans have no value', 'God creates some people solely for destruction', 'a', 'Romans 9:20-23 — "Shall the thing formed say to him that formed it, Why hast thou made me thus? Hath not the potter power over the clay?" The passage emphasises God''s right, not His arbitrariness.'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 5, 'What Hosea prophecy does Paul apply to the inclusion of Gentiles?', 'Hosea 2:23 and 1:10 — "I will call them my people, which were not my people; and her beloved, which was not beloved" — showing God''s plan always included Gentiles', 'Only a passage from Leviticus', 'A prophecy from Ezekiel about dry bones', 'A psalm about the temple', 'a', 'Romans 9:25-26 — "I will call them my people, which were not my people; and her beloved, which was not beloved. And it shall come to pass, that in the place where it was said unto them, Ye are not my people; there shall they be called the children of the living God."'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 6, 'What Isaiah quotation does Paul use to show that only a remnant of Israel would be saved?', 'Isaiah 10:22-23 — "Though the number of the children of Israel be as the sand of the sea, a remnant shall be saved"', 'Isaiah 53 — the suffering servant', 'Isaiah 40:31 — they that wait upon the Lord', 'Isaiah 6:3 — Holy, holy, holy', 'a', 'Romans 9:27 — "Esaias also crieth concerning Israel, Though the number of the children of Israel be as the sand of the sea, a remnant shall be saved."'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 7, 'Why did Israel fail to attain righteousness according to verse 32?', 'Because they sought it not by faith, but as it were by the works of the law — they stumbled at the stumbling stone', 'Because they did not have the law', 'Because they were not descended from Abraham', 'Because they lived outside the promised land', 'a', 'Romans 9:32 — "Wherefore? Because they sought it not by faith, but as it were by the works of the law. For they stumbled at that stumblingstone."'),
('Romans', 9, 'adults', 8, 'How does Romans 9 balance divine sovereignty and human responsibility?', 'Paul presents God''s sovereign election as the foundation of salvation while in chapters 9-10 he also presents Israel''s unbelief as culpable — holding both truths in tension without resolving the mystery', 'It teaches only divine sovereignty', 'It teaches only human free will', 'It resolves the tension completely', 'a', 'Romans 9-10 — Chapter 9 emphasises God''s sovereign mercy (v.16), while chapter 10 emphasises Israel''s wilful unbelief (10:21). Paul holds both truths without eliminating either.');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 10 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 10, 'kids', 1, 'What should you confess with your mouth to be saved?', 'That Jesus is Lord', 'That you are a good person', 'That you go to church', 'That you follow rules', 'a', 'Romans 10:9 — "That if thou shalt confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus, and shalt believe in thine heart that God hath raised him from the dead, thou shalt be saved."'),
('Romans', 10, 'kids', 2, 'Does God treat Jews and non-Jews differently when they call on Him?', 'No, the same Lord is rich unto all that call upon Him', 'Yes, He only helps Jewish people', 'Yes, He only helps non-Jewish people', 'He helps no one', 'a', 'Romans 10:12 — "For there is no difference between the Jew and the Greek: for the same Lord over all is rich unto all that call upon him."'),
('Romans', 10, 'kids', 3, 'How beautiful are the feet of those who bring good news?', 'Very beautiful — How beautiful are the feet of them that preach the gospel of peace', 'Not beautiful at all', 'Only if they wear nice shoes', 'Only if they are fast runners', 'a', 'Romans 10:15 — "How beautiful are the feet of them that preach the gospel of peace, and bring glad tidings of good things!"'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 10, 'teens', 1, 'What is the difference between Israel''s zeal and true knowledge?', 'They had a zeal of God, but not according to knowledge — seeking their own righteousness instead of submitting to God''s', 'Their zeal and knowledge were perfectly balanced', 'They had no zeal at all', 'Their knowledge was greater than their zeal', 'a', 'Romans 10:2-3 — "For I bear them record that they have a zeal of God, but not according to knowledge. For they being ignorant of God''s righteousness, and going about to establish their own righteousness, have not submitted themselves unto the righteousness of God."'),
('Romans', 10, 'teens', 2, 'Who is the end (goal/fulfilment) of the law for righteousness?', 'Christ — for righteousness to every one that believeth', 'Moses', 'The high priest', 'The prophets', 'a', 'Romans 10:4 — "For Christ is the end of the law for righteousness to every one that believeth."'),
('Romans', 10, 'teens', 3, 'What two things does Romans 10:9 say are needed for salvation?', 'Confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus and believe in thine heart that God hath raised Him from the dead', 'Keep all the commandments and do good works', 'Be baptised and join a church', 'Give all your money and fast every day', 'a', 'Romans 10:9 — "That if thou shalt confess with thy mouth the Lord Jesus, and shalt believe in thine heart that God hath raised him from the dead, thou shalt be saved."'),
('Romans', 10, 'teens', 4, 'What logical chain does Paul build about hearing the gospel?', 'They cannot call on one they have not believed; they cannot believe without hearing; they cannot hear without a preacher; and a preacher must be sent', 'People automatically know the gospel', 'Hearing is unnecessary for faith', 'Preaching is outdated and unnecessary', 'a', 'Romans 10:14-15 — "How then shall they call on him in whom they have not believed? and how shall they believe in him of whom they have not heard? and how shall they hear without a preacher? And how shall they preach, except they be sent?"'),
('Romans', 10, 'teens', 5, 'How does faith come according to verse 17?', 'Faith cometh by hearing, and hearing by the word of God', 'Faith comes by seeing miracles', 'Faith comes by studying philosophy', 'Faith comes naturally without any help', 'a', 'Romans 10:17 — "So then faith cometh by hearing, and hearing by the word of God."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 1, 'What does Paul mean by "Christ is the end of the law" (telos)?', 'Christ is both the goal (fulfilment) and the termination of the law as a means of achieving righteousness — He accomplished what the law pointed to but could not achieve', 'Christ destroyed the law completely', 'The law continues unchanged for believers', 'Christ merely added to the law', 'a', 'Romans 10:4 — "For Christ is the end of the law for righteousness to every one that believeth." The Greek telos means both goal/aim and conclusion.'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 2, 'What Deuteronomy passage does Paul reinterpret in verses 6-8?', 'Deuteronomy 30:12-14 — Paul applies Moses'' words about the accessibility of the law to the accessibility of Christ and the gospel message', 'Deuteronomy 5 — the Ten Commandments', 'Deuteronomy 28 — blessings and curses', 'Deuteronomy 18 — the prophet to come', 'a', 'Romans 10:6-8 — Paul draws on Deuteronomy 30:12-14, reinterpreting the "word" that is near (in thy mouth and heart) as the word of faith that he preaches.'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 3, 'What is the relationship between heart belief and mouth confession in verse 9?', 'Heart belief in the resurrection secures righteousness before God, while mouth confession demonstrates and expresses that inward faith publicly — both are aspects of genuine saving faith', 'Confession alone saves without belief', 'Belief alone saves without any expression', 'They are unrelated requirements', 'a', 'Romans 10:9-10 — "With the heart man believeth unto righteousness; and with the mouth confession is made unto salvation." Internal faith and external confession are two sides of the same reality.'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 4, 'What Joel prophecy does Paul cite to prove universal access to salvation?', 'Joel 2:32 — "Whosoever shall call upon the name of the Lord shall be saved" — extending the promise beyond ethnic boundaries', 'Joel 1 — the locust plague', 'Joel 3 — the valley of decision', 'Joel 2:28 — the outpouring of the Spirit', 'a', 'Romans 10:13 — "For whosoever shall call upon the name of the Lord shall be saved" (Joel 2:32).'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 5, 'What Isaiah passage does Paul quote about beautiful feet?', 'Isaiah 52:7 — "How beautiful upon the mountains are the feet of him that bringeth good tidings, that publisheth peace"', 'Isaiah 53 — the suffering servant', 'Isaiah 40 — comfort ye my people', 'Isaiah 6 — the throne room vision', 'a', 'Romans 10:15 — "How beautiful are the feet of them that preach the gospel of peace" (Isaiah 52:7).'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 6, 'How does Paul use Isaiah 53:1 to explain Israel''s unbelief?', '"Lord, who hath believed our report?" — showing that unbelief in the gospel was prophesied and is not a failure of the message but of the hearers', 'Isaiah 53:1 is about a different subject', 'Israel never heard the message', 'The prophets predicted universal belief', 'a', 'Romans 10:16 — "But they have not all obeyed the gospel. For Esaias saith, Lord, who hath believed our report?"'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 7, 'How does Paul prove that Israel did hear the gospel?', 'He quotes Psalm 19:4 — "Their sound went into all the earth, and their words unto the ends of the world" — Israel cannot claim ignorance', 'Israel never had the opportunity to hear', 'The gospel was preached only in Jerusalem', 'Only Gentiles heard the gospel', 'a', 'Romans 10:18 — "But I say, Have they not heard? Yes verily, their sound went into all the earth, and their words unto the ends of the world."'),
('Romans', 10, 'adults', 8, 'What does Paul quote from Isaiah 65:2 about God''s posture toward Israel?', '"All day long I have stretched forth my hands unto a disobedient and gainsaying people" — God persistently offered grace, but Israel stubbornly refused', 'God abandoned Israel without warning', 'God never reached out to Israel', 'Israel eagerly accepted God''s invitation', 'a', 'Romans 10:21 — "But to Israel he saith, All day long I have stretched forth my hands unto a disobedient and gainsaying people."');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 11 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 11, 'kids', 1, 'Has God completely rejected Israel?', 'No, God has not cast away His people — Paul himself is an Israelite as proof', 'Yes, God rejected them forever', 'God never chose Israel', 'Israel was replaced completely', 'a', 'Romans 11:1 — "I say then, Hath God cast away his people? God forbid. For I also am an Israelite, of the seed of Abraham, of the tribe of Benjamin."'),
('Romans', 11, 'kids', 2, 'What picture does Paul use about an olive tree?', 'Wild branches (Gentiles) were grafted into the olive tree, and natural branches (Israel) were broken off', 'The tree was chopped down completely', 'Only Jewish branches grow on the tree', 'The tree has no branches', 'a', 'Romans 11:17 — "And if some of the branches be broken off, and thou, being a wild olive tree, wert graffed in among them."'),
('Romans', 11, 'kids', 3, 'What does Paul say about how deep God''s wisdom is?', 'It is so deep that no one can fully understand it', 'It is easy for everyone to understand', 'Only Paul understands it', 'It does not exist', 'a', 'Romans 11:33 — "O the depth of the riches both of the wisdom and knowledge of God! how unsearchable are his judgments, and his ways past finding out!"'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 11, 'teens', 1, 'What Old Testament example does Paul give of a faithful remnant?', 'In Elijah''s time, God reserved 7,000 who had not bowed the knee to Baal — even so, there is a remnant according to the election of grace', 'Noah''s family on the ark', 'The Israelites crossing the Red Sea', 'David''s mighty men', 'a', 'Romans 11:4-5 — "I have reserved to myself seven thousand men, who have not bowed the knee to the image of Baal. Even so then at this present time also there is a remnant according to the election of grace."'),
('Romans', 11, 'teens', 2, 'What good came from Israel''s stumbling?', 'Salvation came to the Gentiles, to provoke Israel to jealousy', 'Nothing good came from it', 'The law was destroyed', 'The temple was rebuilt', 'a', 'Romans 11:11 — "Through their fall salvation is come unto the Gentiles, for to provoke them to jealousy."'),
('Romans', 11, 'teens', 3, 'What warning does Paul give to Gentile believers?', 'Do not be arrogant — if God did not spare the natural branches (Israel), He will not spare you either', 'Gentiles are permanently safe no matter what', 'Gentiles are superior to Jews', 'Gentiles can boast against Israel', 'a', 'Romans 11:21 — "For if God spared not the natural branches, take heed lest he also spare not thee."'),
('Romans', 11, 'teens', 4, 'What does Paul say will eventually happen to Israel?', 'All Israel shall be saved — the Deliverer shall come out of Sion and turn away ungodliness from Jacob', 'Israel will remain hardened forever', 'Israel will be permanently replaced', 'Israel no longer matters in God''s plan', 'a', 'Romans 11:26 — "And so all Israel shall be saved: as it is written, There shall come out of Sion the Deliverer, and shall turn away ungodliness from Jacob."'),
('Romans', 11, 'teens', 5, 'What does Paul say about God''s gifts and calling?', 'The gifts and calling of God are without repentance (irrevocable)', 'God takes back His gifts when people disobey', 'God''s calling can be cancelled', 'Only certain gifts are permanent', 'a', 'Romans 11:29 — "For the gifts and calling of God are without repentance."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 1, 'What does Paul''s own conversion prove about God''s plan for Israel?', 'As a Benjamite and Israelite, Paul himself is proof that God has not entirely rejected Israel — a remnant exists by grace', 'Paul''s conversion is unrelated to Israel', 'Paul ceased being an Israelite at conversion', 'God replaced Israel with Paul alone', 'a', 'Romans 11:1 — "Hath God cast away his people? God forbid. For I also am an Israelite, of the seed of Abraham, of the tribe of Benjamin."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 2, 'What does "election of grace" versus "works" mean in verses 5-6?', 'The remnant is chosen by God''s unmerited favour, not by their own merit — if by grace, then it is no more of works, otherwise grace is no more grace', 'Grace and works can be combined', 'Works determine who receives grace', 'Grace is a reward for effort', 'a', 'Romans 11:5-6 — "There is a remnant according to the election of grace. And if by grace, then is it no more of works: otherwise grace is no more grace."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 3, 'What does the olive tree metaphor teach about the relationship between Israel and the church?', 'The church is grafted into Israel''s covenantal heritage (the root), not a replacement — Gentile believers partake of the root and fatness of the olive tree', 'The church replaces Israel entirely', 'Israel and the church are completely separate', 'The olive tree represents the Roman Empire', 'a', 'Romans 11:17-18 — "Thou, being a wild olive tree, wert graffed in among them, and with them partakest of the root and fatness of the olive tree; Boast not against the branches."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 4, 'What is the "mystery" Paul reveals in verse 25?', 'Blindness in part has happened to Israel until the fulness of the Gentiles be come in — then all Israel shall be saved', 'The mystery is that Israel was never chosen', 'The mystery is that Gentiles will eventually be rejected', 'The mystery has never been revealed', 'a', 'Romans 11:25-26 — "Blindness in part is happened to Israel, until the fulness of the Gentiles be come in. And so all Israel shall be saved."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 5, 'What Isaiah and Jeremiah prophecies does Paul cite regarding Israel''s future salvation?', 'Isaiah 59:20-21 and Isaiah 27:9 (with Jeremiah 31:33-34) — "The Deliverer shall come out of Sion... this is my covenant unto them, when I shall take away their sins"', 'Only Psalm 23', 'Only Genesis 12', 'Only Ezekiel 37', 'a', 'Romans 11:26-27 — "There shall come out of Sion the Deliverer, and shall turn away ungodliness from Jacob: For this is my covenant unto them, when I shall take away their sins."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 6, 'How does Paul explain the paradox of Israel being both enemies and beloved?', 'As concerning the gospel, they are enemies for the Gentiles'' sake; but as touching the election, they are beloved for the fathers'' sakes — God''s covenant faithfulness endures', 'Israel can only be one or the other', 'Being enemies cancels being beloved', 'The paradox cannot be explained', 'a', 'Romans 11:28 — "As concerning the gospel, they are enemies for your sakes: but as touching the election, they are beloved for the fathers'' sakes."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 7, 'What does Paul mean by "God hath concluded them all in unbelief"?', 'God has shut up all people — both Jews and Gentiles — under disobedience so that He might have mercy upon all, demonstrating that salvation is entirely by grace', 'God wants everyone to remain in unbelief', 'Only Gentiles are in unbelief', 'Unbelief is permanent for everyone', 'a', 'Romans 11:32 — "For God hath concluded them all in unbelief, that he might have mercy upon all."'),
('Romans', 11, 'adults', 8, 'What is the significance of Paul''s doxology in verses 33-36?', 'It expresses overwhelming awe at God''s wisdom in orchestrating salvation history — His judgments are unsearchable, His ways past finding out, and all things are from, through, and to Him', 'It is a routine closing greeting', 'It summarises Paul''s travel plans', 'It is addressed to the Roman emperor', 'a', 'Romans 11:33,36 — "O the depth of the riches both of the wisdom and knowledge of God! how unsearchable are his judgments, and his ways past finding out!... For of him, and through him, and to him, are all things: to whom be glory for ever. Amen."');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 12 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 12, 'kids', 1, 'What does Paul say we should give to God as a living sacrifice?', 'Our bodies — present your bodies a living sacrifice', 'Our money only', 'Our best clothes', 'Our favourite toys', 'a', 'Romans 12:1 — "I beseech you therefore, brethren, by the mercies of God, that ye present your bodies a living sacrifice, holy, acceptable unto God."'),
('Romans', 12, 'kids', 2, 'How should we treat people who are mean to us?', 'Be kind to them — overcome evil with good', 'Be mean back to them', 'Ignore them forever', 'Run away and hide', 'a', 'Romans 12:21 — "Be not overcome of evil, but overcome evil with good."'),
('Romans', 12, 'kids', 3, 'Should we think of ourselves as better than others?', 'No, we should not think more highly of ourselves than we ought to think', 'Yes, if we are very smart', 'Yes, if we go to church', 'Yes, if our parents are important', 'a', 'Romans 12:3 — "For I say... to every man that is among you, not to think of himself more highly than he ought to think; but to think soberly."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 12, 'teens', 1, 'What should we not be conformed to?', 'This world — be not conformed to this world, but be ye transformed by the renewing of your mind', 'The teachings of Jesus', 'The will of God', 'The pattern of the apostles', 'a', 'Romans 12:2 — "And be not conformed to this world: but be ye transformed by the renewing of your mind, that ye may prove what is that good, and acceptable, and perfect, will of God."'),
('Romans', 12, 'teens', 2, 'What does Paul teach about spiritual gifts using the body analogy?', 'As one body has many members with different functions, so believers have different gifts and should use them faithfully', 'Everyone has the same gift', 'Only leaders have gifts', 'Gifts are unimportant', 'a', 'Romans 12:4-6 — "For as we have many members in one body, and all members have not the same office: So we, being many, are one body in Christ... Having then gifts differing according to the grace that is given to us."'),
('Romans', 12, 'teens', 3, 'What should our love be like?', 'Without dissimulation (hypocrisy) — genuine and sincere', 'Fake and for show', 'Only for people we like', 'Conditional on being loved back', 'a', 'Romans 12:9 — "Let love be without dissimulation. Abhor that which is evil; cleave to that which is good."'),
('Romans', 12, 'teens', 4, 'How should believers respond to persecution?', 'Bless them which persecute you: bless, and curse not', 'Curse them and seek revenge', 'Pretend it is not happening', 'Fight back with equal force', 'a', 'Romans 12:14 — "Bless them which persecute you: bless, and curse not."'),
('Romans', 12, 'teens', 5, 'What does Paul say about taking revenge?', 'Do not avenge yourselves — leave room for God''s wrath, for vengeance is mine, saith the Lord', 'Take revenge quickly', 'Revenge is a Christian duty', 'Only take revenge on serious offences', 'a', 'Romans 12:19 — "Dearly beloved, avenge not yourselves, but rather give place unto wrath: for it is written, Vengeance is mine; I will repay, saith the Lord."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 1, 'Why does Paul say "by the mercies of God" before his ethical exhortation?', 'Christian ethics flow from gospel grace — the mercies described in chapters 1-11 are the motivation for the obedience described in chapters 12-16', 'It is merely a polite greeting', 'He is quoting a Jewish prayer', 'It has no connection to the preceding chapters', 'a', 'Romans 12:1 — "I beseech you therefore, brethren, by the mercies of God." The word "therefore" connects all of Paul''s theology (ch.1-11) to the practical Christian life.'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 2, 'What does "living sacrifice" mean in contrast to Old Testament sacrifices?', 'Unlike OT animal sacrifices that died, believers offer their living bodies in ongoing, active devotion to God — a continuous act of worship in daily life', 'It means a one-time ritual', 'It refers to animal sacrifice continuing', 'It is a metaphor with no practical application', 'a', 'Romans 12:1 — "Present your bodies a living sacrifice, holy, acceptable unto God, which is your reasonable service." The term logiken latreian means rational/spiritual worship.'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 3, 'What gifts does Paul list in verses 6-8?', 'Prophecy, ministry (service), teaching, exhortation, giving, ruling (leadership), and showing mercy', 'Only tongues and healing', 'Only preaching and teaching', 'Only prophecy and apostleship', 'a', 'Romans 12:6-8 — Paul lists seven gifts: prophecy, ministry, teaching, exhortation, giving (with simplicity), ruling (with diligence), showing mercy (with cheerfulness).'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 4, 'What does "Be not overcome of evil, but overcome evil with good" mean ethically?', 'Christians should not let evil dictate their response — instead, they should proactively defeat evil by responding with good, breaking the cycle of retaliation', 'Christians should avoid all contact with evil people', 'Evil always wins in the end', 'Good and evil are equally powerful', 'a', 'Romans 12:21 — "Be not overcome of evil, but overcome evil with good." This summarises the entire ethic of non-retaliation.'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 5, 'What Proverbs passage does Paul quote about treating enemies?', 'Proverbs 25:21-22 — "If thine enemy hunger, feed him; if he thirst, give him drink: for in so doing thou shalt heap coals of fire on his head"', 'Proverbs 1:7 — the fear of the Lord', 'Proverbs 3:5-6 — trust in the Lord', 'Proverbs 31 — the virtuous woman', 'a', 'Romans 12:20 — "If thine enemy hunger, feed him; if he thirst, give him drink: for in so doing thou shalt heap coals of fire on his head" (Proverbs 25:21-22).'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 6, 'What does "heaping coals of fire on his head" likely mean?', 'Acts of kindness may produce burning shame and conviction in an enemy, leading to repentance — a redemptive, not vengeful, purpose', 'Literally burning your enemy', 'Cursing them secretly', 'Hoping for their destruction', 'a', 'Romans 12:20 — "Thou shalt heap coals of fire on his head." Most scholars interpret this as the burning conviction of conscience that kindness produces, potentially leading to repentance.'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 7, 'How does "be not wise in your own conceits" relate to humility?', 'Paul warns against intellectual arrogance — believers should associate with the lowly rather than seeking high positions, recognising that all wisdom comes from God', 'Believers should not pursue education', 'Only leaders should be humble', 'Humility means pretending to be ignorant', 'a', 'Romans 12:16 — "Be of the same mind one toward another. Mind not high things, but condescend to men of low estate. Be not wise in your own conceits."'),
('Romans', 12, 'adults', 8, 'What does "provide things honest in the sight of all men" teach about Christian testimony?', 'Believers should live with transparent integrity so that even unbelievers can see their honourable conduct — public witness matters', 'Only private morality matters', 'Reputation is irrelevant for Christians', 'Only behaviour in church counts', 'a', 'Romans 12:17 — "Provide things honest in the sight of all men." Paul echoes Proverbs 3:4 (LXX), emphasising visible integrity before a watching world.');

-- ═══════════════ CHAPTERS 13–16 ═══════════════

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 13 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 13, 'kids', 1, 'What does Paul say about obeying rulers and governments?', 'Everyone should be subject to the higher powers, for they are ordained by God', 'Nobody should obey any government', 'Only kings should be obeyed', 'Only religious leaders should be obeyed', 'a', 'Romans 13:1 — "Let every soul be subject unto the higher powers. For there is no power but of God: the powers that be are ordained of God."'),
('Romans', 13, 'kids', 2, 'What commandment sums up all the others about how we treat people?', 'Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself', 'Thou shalt not eat certain foods', 'Thou shalt build a temple', 'Thou shalt travel to Jerusalem', 'a', 'Romans 13:9 — "Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself."'),
('Romans', 13, 'kids', 3, 'What does Paul say we should put on?', 'The armour of light and the Lord Jesus Christ', 'Heavy golden robes', 'A crown and sceptre', 'Warm winter clothes', 'a', 'Romans 13:12,14 — "Let us put on the armour of light... But put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 13, 'teens', 1, 'Why does Paul say rulers are not a terror to good works?', 'Rulers are God''s ministers — they bear the sword to punish evil and praise good, serving as God''s instrument of justice', 'Rulers never punish anyone', 'Rulers only exist to collect taxes', 'Rulers have no real authority', 'a', 'Romans 13:3-4 — "For rulers are not a terror to good works, but to the evil... For he is the minister of God to thee for good."'),
('Romans', 13, 'teens', 2, 'What debts does Paul say we should pay?', 'Give to all their dues: tribute, custom, fear, and honour to whom each is owed', 'Only money debts', 'No debts — Christians should never owe anything', 'Only debts to the church', 'a', 'Romans 13:7 — "Render therefore to all their dues: tribute to whom tribute is due; custom to whom custom; fear to whom fear; honour to whom honour."'),
('Romans', 13, 'teens', 3, 'What is the only debt we should always owe?', 'To love one another — for he that loveth another hath fulfilled the law', 'Money debts to the bank', 'Service to the government', 'Labour to our employers', 'a', 'Romans 13:8 — "Owe no man any thing, but to love one another: for he that loveth another hath fulfilled the law."'),
('Romans', 13, 'teens', 4, 'Why does Paul say it is time to wake out of sleep?', 'Our salvation is nearer than when we believed — the night is far spent and the day is at hand', 'Because it is morning time', 'Because there is work to do at the temple', 'Because enemies are approaching', 'a', 'Romans 13:11-12 — "And that, knowing the time, that now it is high time to awake out of sleep: for now is our salvation nearer than when we believed. The night is far spent, the day is at hand."'),
('Romans', 13, 'teens', 5, 'What kind of behaviour does Paul say to cast off?', 'Works of darkness — rioting, drunkenness, strife, and envying', 'Works of light', 'Acts of kindness', 'Prayer and worship', 'a', 'Romans 13:12-13 — "Let us cast off the works of darkness, and let us put on the armour of light. Let us walk honestly, as in the day; not in rioting and drunkenness, not in chambering and wantonness, not in strife and envying."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 1, 'What is Paul''s theological basis for submission to government?', 'All governing authority is ordained (established) by God — to resist the authority is to resist God''s ordinance', 'Government exists independently of God', 'Only theocracies are ordained by God', 'Government is inherently evil but necessary', 'a', 'Romans 13:1-2 — "There is no power but of God: the powers that be are ordained of God. Whosoever therefore resisteth the power, resisteth the ordinance of God."'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 2, 'What does the ruler bearing the sword signify?', 'The divinely delegated authority to use coercive force — including capital punishment — to maintain justice and punish evildoers', 'The sword is merely ceremonial', 'Rulers should use swords in worship', 'The sword represents writing implements', 'a', 'Romans 13:4 — "For he is the minister of God to thee for good. But if thou do that which is evil, be afraid; for he beareth not the sword in vain: for he is the minister of God, a revenger to execute wrath upon him that doeth evil."'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 3, 'How does Paul ground the command to love one''s neighbour in the Decalogue?', 'He lists several commandments (adultery, murder, theft, coveting) and says they are all summed up in "love thy neighbour as thyself" — love fulfils the law because it does no harm', 'The Decalogue is abolished by love', 'Love replaces individual commandments', 'Only the love commandment matters', 'a', 'Romans 13:9-10 — "Thou shalt not commit adultery, Thou shalt not kill, Thou shalt not steal... it is briefly comprehended in this saying, namely, Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself. Love worketh no ill to his neighbour: therefore love is the fulfilling of the law."'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 4, 'What eschatological motivation does Paul provide for holy living?', 'The day of Christ''s return is nearer now than when we first believed — urgency of the parousia should motivate present obedience', 'There is no urgency at all', 'The day of the Lord has already passed', 'Holy living has no connection to future events', 'a', 'Romans 13:11-12 — "Now it is high time to awake out of sleep: for now is our salvation nearer than when we believed. The night is far spent, the day is at hand."'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 5, 'What does "put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ" mean practically?', 'To clothe oneself with Christ''s character, virtues, and priorities — making Him the governing reality of daily life, and making no provision for the flesh', 'To wear religious clothing', 'To memorise facts about Jesus', 'To attend church more frequently', 'a', 'Romans 13:14 — "But put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ, and make not provision for the flesh, to fulfil the lusts thereof."'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 6, 'How does Romans 13:14 connect to Augustine''s conversion?', 'Augustine records in his Confessions that this verse was the one he read at the moment of his conversion — "put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ" — ending his struggle with sin', 'Augustine never read Romans', 'Romans 13:14 is rarely cited in church history', 'Augustine preferred other Pauline epistles', 'a', 'Romans 13:14 — "Put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ." Augustine (Confessions 8.12) describes reading this verse in the garden in Milan as the turning point of his conversion in AD 386.'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 7, 'What are the limits of submission to government according to broader biblical theology?', 'While Romans 13 teaches general submission, Acts 5:29 ("We ought to obey God rather than men") shows that when government commands what God forbids or forbids what God commands, believers must obey God', 'There are no limits — absolute obedience is required', 'Christians should never obey any government', 'Only Jewish governments deserve obedience', 'a', 'Romans 13:1 must be read alongside Acts 5:29, Daniel 3, and Daniel 6 — submission to government is the norm but not absolute when it contradicts God''s commands.'),
('Romans', 13, 'adults', 8, 'What does Paul mean by "the day is at hand" in verse 12?', 'The day of Christ''s return (parousia) draws ever closer — Paul uses dawn/night imagery to emphasise that believers live in the final era between Christ''s first and second comings', 'Literal sunrise is approaching', 'A Jewish festival day', 'The Roman new year', 'a', 'Romans 13:12 — "The night is far spent, the day is at hand: let us therefore cast off the works of darkness, and let us put on the armour of light."');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 14 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 14, 'kids', 1, 'Should we judge other Christians for what they eat or don''t eat?', 'No, we should not judge or despise one another over food', 'Yes, food rules are the most important thing', 'Yes, everyone should eat the same things', 'Only leaders can decide what others eat', 'a', 'Romans 14:3 — "Let not him that eateth despise him that eateth not; and let not him which eateth not judge him that eateth: for God hath received him."'),
('Romans', 14, 'kids', 2, 'Who do we all belong to, whether we live or die?', 'The Lord — we are the Lord''s', 'Ourselves only', 'Our families', 'Our country', 'a', 'Romans 14:8 — "For whether we live, we live unto the Lord; and whether we die, we die unto the Lord: whether we live therefore, or die, we are the Lord''s."'),
('Romans', 14, 'kids', 3, 'What should we try not to do to other Christians?', 'Put a stumbling block or occasion to fall in their way', 'Make them laugh', 'Teach them the Bible', 'Pray for them', 'a', 'Romans 14:13 — "Let us not therefore judge one another any more: but judge this rather, that no man put a stumblingblock or an occasion to fall in his brother''s way."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 14, 'teens', 1, 'What does Paul say about people who are weak in faith?', 'Receive them, but not to doubtful disputations (quarrels over opinions)', 'Reject them until they become strong', 'Argue with them until they agree with you', 'Ignore them completely', 'a', 'Romans 14:1 — "Him that is weak in the faith receive ye, but not to doubtful disputations."'),
('Romans', 14, 'teens', 2, 'What does Paul say about one person esteeming one day above another?', 'Let every man be fully persuaded in his own mind — one person esteems one day, another esteems every day alike', 'Everyone must observe the same holy days', 'Holy days are meaningless for all Christians', 'Only Jewish holy days matter', 'a', 'Romans 14:5 — "One man esteemeth one day above another: another esteemeth every day alike. Let every man be fully persuaded in his own mind."'),
('Romans', 14, 'teens', 3, 'Before whose judgment seat shall we all stand?', 'The judgment seat of Christ', 'The judgment seat of Moses', 'The judgment seat of Caesar', 'The judgment seat of the high priest', 'a', 'Romans 14:10 — "For we shall all stand before the judgment seat of Christ."'),
('Romans', 14, 'teens', 4, 'What is the kingdom of God according to verse 17?', 'Not meat and drink, but righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost', 'Only about food and drink rules', 'A political kingdom on earth', 'A place reserved for a few', 'a', 'Romans 14:17 — "For the kingdom of God is not meat and drink; but righteousness, and peace, and joy in the Holy Ghost."'),
('Romans', 14, 'teens', 5, 'What should we pursue according to verse 19?', 'Things which make for peace and things wherewith one may edify another', 'Arguments and debates', 'Personal freedom above all', 'Wealth and comfort', 'a', 'Romans 14:19 — "Let us therefore follow after the things which make for peace, and things wherewith one may edify another."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 1, 'What are the "disputable matters" (adiaphora) Paul addresses in this chapter?', 'Matters of conscience not clearly commanded in Scripture — such as dietary choices and observance of special days — where Christians may legitimately differ', 'Core doctrines like the resurrection', 'The deity of Christ', 'The authority of Scripture', 'a', 'Romans 14:1-6 — Paul addresses food (vegetarianism vs. eating all things) and days (holy day observance vs. treating all days alike) as matters where Christians should tolerate differing convictions.'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 2, 'What does Paul mean by the "weak" and "strong" in faith?', 'The "weak" have overly scrupulous consciences about non-essential matters; the "strong" (including Paul) have freedom but must not despise the weak', 'The weak are unbelievers', 'The strong are arrogant', 'Both terms are negative', 'a', 'Romans 14:2,14; 15:1 — The weak eat only vegetables out of conscience; the strong believe all things are clean. Paul identifies with the strong (15:1) but calls for mutual acceptance.'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 3, 'What does "every knee shall bow" in verse 11 quote, and what does it prove?', 'Isaiah 45:23 — applied to Christ, proving His deity and universal authority as the judge before whom all will give account', 'It quotes Psalm 23', 'It refers to earthly kings only', 'It has no OT source', 'a', 'Romans 14:11 — "For it is written, As I live, saith the Lord, every knee shall bow to me, and every tongue shall confess to God" (Isaiah 45:23). Paul applies this to Christ''s judgment seat.'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 4, 'What does Paul mean by "nothing is unclean of itself"?', 'No food is inherently sinful — but if someone''s conscience deems it unclean, then to that person it is unclean, and eating against conscience is sin', 'All moral distinctions are abolished', 'Sin is subjective in all matters', 'Conscience is always reliable', 'a', 'Romans 14:14 — "I know, and am persuaded by the Lord Jesus, that there is nothing unclean of itself: but to him that esteemeth any thing to be unclean, to him it is unclean."'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 5, 'What principle does Paul establish about using freedom at the expense of another?', 'If your food causes a brother to stumble, you are no longer walking in love — do not destroy with your meat him for whom Christ died', 'Freedom should be exercised without any restriction', 'The strong have no obligation to the weak', 'Love does not apply to food choices', 'a', 'Romans 14:15 — "But if thy brother be grieved with thy meat, now walkest thou not charitably. Destroy not him with thy meat, for whom Christ died."'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 6, 'What does "whatsoever is not of faith is sin" in verse 23 mean?', 'Any action done against one''s own conscience — even if the act itself is not sinful — becomes sin because it violates the person''s conviction before God', 'Only things related to faith are sinful', 'Faith eliminates all possibility of sin', 'This verse only applies to food', 'a', 'Romans 14:23 — "And he that doubteth is damned if he eat, because he eateth not of faith: for whatsoever is not of faith is sin." Acting against conscience, even in permitted matters, is sin.'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 7, 'How does the judgment seat of Christ differ from the Great White Throne judgment?', 'The judgment seat (bema) of Christ evaluates believers'' works for rewards (cf. 1 Corinthians 3:12-15; 2 Corinthians 5:10), while the Great White Throne (Revelation 20:11-15) judges the unsaved', 'They are the same judgment', 'The bema judges only apostles', 'The Great White Throne is for believers', 'a', 'Romans 14:10,12 — "We shall all stand before the judgment seat of Christ... every one of us shall give account of himself to God." The bema evaluates the Christian''s stewardship, not salvation.'),
('Romans', 14, 'adults', 8, 'What overarching principle governs Christian liberty in Romans 14?', 'Love for fellow believers takes precedence over personal freedom — the exercise of liberty must be governed by its effect on others'' faith and conscience', 'Personal freedom is absolute', 'Rules should be imposed on everyone equally', 'Liberty means doing whatever one desires', 'a', 'Romans 14:13,15,19-21 — The entire chapter teaches that Christian freedom is real but must be voluntarily limited by love, edification, and concern for weaker brethren.');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 15 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 15, 'kids', 1, 'What should strong Christians do for weak Christians?', 'Bear their weaknesses and not just please themselves', 'Ignore them', 'Make fun of them', 'Tell them to go away', 'a', 'Romans 15:1 — "We then that are strong ought to bear the infirmities of the weak, and not to please ourselves."'),
('Romans', 15, 'kids', 2, 'What does Paul want the God of hope to fill believers with?', 'All joy and peace in believing', 'Fear and sadness', 'Anger and frustration', 'Worry and doubt', 'a', 'Romans 15:13 — "Now the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing, that ye may abound in hope, through the power of the Holy Ghost."'),
('Romans', 15, 'kids', 3, 'Where did Paul want to travel to preach the gospel?', 'Spain — passing through Rome on the way', 'Egypt', 'India', 'China', 'a', 'Romans 15:24 — "Whensoever I take my journey into Spain, I will come to you."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 15, 'teens', 1, 'What does Paul say Christ did not do?', 'He pleased not Himself — the reproaches of them that reproached God fell on Him', 'He pleased Himself at all times', 'He avoided all suffering', 'He sought only His own comfort', 'a', 'Romans 15:3 — "For even Christ pleased not himself; but, as it is written, The reproaches of them that reproached thee fell on me."'),
('Romans', 15, 'teens', 2, 'Why were the Old Testament Scriptures written?', 'For our learning, that we through patience and comfort of the scriptures might have hope', 'Only for the Jewish people of that time', 'Only as historical records', 'Only for priests to read', 'a', 'Romans 15:4 — "For whatsoever things were written aforetime were written for our learning, that we through patience and comfort of the scriptures might have hope."'),
('Romans', 15, 'teens', 3, 'Why did Christ become a minister to the circumcision (Jews)?', 'To confirm the promises made unto the fathers and that the Gentiles might glorify God for His mercy', 'To establish a new Jewish kingdom', 'To abolish the Gentiles', 'To create a new law', 'a', 'Romans 15:8-9 — "Jesus Christ was a minister of the circumcision for the truth of God, to confirm the promises made unto the fathers: And that the Gentiles might glorify God for his mercy."'),
('Romans', 15, 'teens', 4, 'What was Paul''s ambition in preaching the gospel?', 'To preach where Christ was not yet named, lest he build upon another man''s foundation', 'To preach only in Jerusalem', 'To compete with other apostles', 'To only preach to Jews', 'a', 'Romans 15:20 — "Yea, so have I strived to preach the gospel, not where Christ was named, lest I should build upon another man''s foundation."'),
('Romans', 15, 'teens', 5, 'What practical help were the Gentile churches giving to Jerusalem?', 'A financial collection for the poor saints in Jerusalem', 'Military protection', 'Building materials', 'Food and clothing only', 'a', 'Romans 15:26 — "For it hath pleased them of Macedonia and Achaia to make a certain contribution for the poor saints which are at Jerusalem."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 1, 'What four OT quotations does Paul chain together in verses 9-12 to prove Gentile inclusion?', 'Psalm 18:49, Deuteronomy 32:43, Psalm 117:1, and Isaiah 11:10 — each progressively showing God''s plan for Gentiles to praise Him alongside Israel', 'Only one verse from Psalms', 'No OT quotations are used', 'Only verses from the Pentateuch', 'a', 'Romans 15:9-12 — Paul cites four texts from the Law (Deut 32:43), Prophets (Isa 11:10), and Writings (Ps 18:49; 117:1) to show a comprehensive OT witness to Gentile inclusion.'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 2, 'What does Paul mean by his priestly ministry of the gospel in verse 16?', 'Paul sees his apostolic work as a priestly offering — presenting the Gentiles as a sanctified offering acceptable to God through the Holy Spirit', 'Paul was literally a temple priest', 'Paul performed animal sacrifices', 'Paul sought to restore the Levitical system', 'a', 'Romans 15:16 — "That I should be the minister of Jesus Christ to the Gentiles, ministering the gospel of God, that the offering up of the Gentiles might be acceptable, being sanctified by the Holy Ghost."'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 3, 'What does Paul mean by the "signs and wonders" accompanying his ministry?', 'Miracles performed through the power of the Spirit to authenticate his apostolic message — from Jerusalem round about unto Illyricum, he had fully preached the gospel', 'Paul invented the miracles', 'Signs and wonders were common for everyone', 'These were natural coincidences', 'a', 'Romans 15:19 — "Through mighty signs and wonders, by the power of the Spirit of God; so that from Jerusalem, and round about unto Illyricum, I have fully preached the gospel of Christ."'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 4, 'What Isaiah passage does Paul cite to justify his pioneer missionary strategy?', 'Isaiah 52:15 — "To whom he was not spoken of, they shall see: and they that have not heard shall understand"', 'Isaiah 6 — the call of Isaiah', 'Isaiah 53 — the suffering servant', 'Isaiah 40 — comfort ye my people', 'a', 'Romans 15:21 — "But as it is written, To whom he was not spoken of, they shall see: and they that have not heard shall understand" (Isaiah 52:15).'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 5, 'Why does Paul say the Gentile churches owe Jerusalem a financial debt?', 'If Gentiles have shared in Israel''s spiritual blessings, they ought to minister to them in material things — it is both a duty and an act of fellowship', 'Jerusalem demanded payment', 'Paul forced them to give', 'The money was a tax', 'a', 'Romans 15:27 — "For if the Gentiles have been made partakers of their spiritual things, their duty is also to minister unto them in carnal things."'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 6, 'What three prayer requests does Paul ask the Romans to strive together with him for?', 'Deliverance from unbelievers in Judaea, acceptance of his service by the Jerusalem saints, and that he may come to Rome with joy by the will of God', 'For a new temple in Rome', 'For the emperor''s conversion', 'For an end to all persecution', 'a', 'Romans 15:30-32 — "That I may be delivered from them that do not believe in Judaea; and that my service which I have for Jerusalem may be accepted of the saints; That I may come unto you with joy by the will of God, and may with you be refreshed."'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 7, 'What title does Paul give to God in his benediction of verse 13?', 'The God of hope — who fills believers with all joy and peace in believing, so that they may abound in hope through the power of the Holy Ghost', 'The God of wrath', 'The God of the law', 'The God of judgment', 'a', 'Romans 15:13 — "Now the God of hope fill you with all joy and peace in believing, that ye may abound in hope, through the power of the Holy Ghost."'),
('Romans', 15, 'adults', 8, 'How does Paul''s planned journey to Spain reflect his missionary vision?', 'Paul saw Rome as a staging point for the gospel''s advance to the western end of the known world — demonstrating his conviction that the gospel must reach all nations', 'Spain was simply a vacation destination', 'Paul had relatives in Spain', 'Spain was the only place left', 'a', 'Romans 15:24,28 — "Whensoever I take my journey into Spain, I will come to you... I will come by you into Spain." Paul aimed to plant churches in unreached regions across the entire Roman world.');

-- ═══ Romans Chapter 16 ═══
INSERT INTO chapter_quizzes (book_name, chapter_number, difficulty, question_number, question, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_answer, explanation) VALUES
-- Kids
('Romans', 16, 'kids', 1, 'What does Paul ask the Romans to do to Phoebe?', 'Receive her in the Lord and assist her in whatever she needs', 'Send her away', 'Ignore her', 'Test her knowledge', 'a', 'Romans 16:2 — "That ye receive her in the Lord, as becometh saints, and that ye assist her in whatsoever business she hath need of you."'),
('Romans', 16, 'kids', 2, 'How does Paul say the Romans should greet one another?', 'With a holy kiss', 'With a handshake', 'With a bow', 'With a wave', 'a', 'Romans 16:16 — "Salute one another with an holy kiss."'),
('Romans', 16, 'kids', 3, 'Who does Paul give glory to at the very end of the letter?', 'The only wise God, through Jesus Christ — to whom be glory for ever', 'The Roman emperor', 'The temple priests', 'Himself', 'a', 'Romans 16:27 — "To God only wise, be glory through Jesus Christ for ever. Amen."'),
-- Teens
('Romans', 16, 'teens', 1, 'Who is the first person Paul greets and what does he call her?', 'Phoebe — a servant (deaconess) of the church at Cenchrea and a succourer of many', 'Timothy — his young protégé', 'Peter — the chief apostle', 'Luke — the physician', 'a', 'Romans 16:1 — "I commend unto you Phebe our sister, which is a servant of the church which is at Cenchrea."'),
('Romans', 16, 'teens', 2, 'Who does Paul call his fellow workers who risked their necks for him?', 'Priscilla and Aquila — who laid down their own necks for his life', 'Peter and John', 'James and Andrew', 'Barnabas and Silas', 'a', 'Romans 16:3-4 — "Greet Priscilla and Aquila my helpers in Christ Jesus: Who have for my life laid down their own necks."'),
('Romans', 16, 'teens', 3, 'What does Paul warn the Romans to avoid?', 'Those who cause divisions and offences contrary to the doctrine they learned — avoid them', 'All Gentile believers', 'Anyone who asks questions', 'People who eat different food', 'a', 'Romans 16:17 — "Now I beseech you, brethren, mark them which cause divisions and offences contrary to the doctrine which ye have learned; and avoid them."'),
('Romans', 16, 'teens', 4, 'What does Paul promise God will do to Satan?', 'The God of peace shall bruise Satan under your feet shortly', 'Satan will rule forever', 'Satan and God will make peace', 'Satan will be ignored', 'a', 'Romans 16:20 — "And the God of peace shall bruise Satan under your feet shortly."'),
('Romans', 16, 'teens', 5, 'Who actually wrote (scripted) the letter to the Romans for Paul?', 'Tertius — who salutes the Romans in the Lord', 'Timothy', 'Luke', 'Barnabas', 'a', 'Romans 16:22 — "I Tertius, who wrote this epistle, salute you in the Lord."'),
-- Adults
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 1, 'What does the term "servant" (diakonos) for Phoebe imply about women''s roles in the early church?', 'Phoebe held an official role of service in the church at Cenchrea — whether as a formal deaconess or as a recognized servant, she was entrusted with delivering this important letter', 'Women had no role in the church', 'Phoebe was merely Paul''s personal servant', 'The term has no significance', 'a', 'Romans 16:1-2 — "Phebe our sister, which is a servant (diakonos) of the church which is at Cenchrea: for she hath been a succourer of many, and of myself also."'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 2, 'How many individuals does Paul greet by name in this chapter, and what does this reveal?', 'Approximately 26-28 individuals — remarkably, Paul knew this many people in a church he had never visited, showing the interconnectedness of the early church through travel and mission', 'Only two people', 'He greets no one by name', 'Exactly twelve people', 'a', 'Romans 16:3-16 — Paul greets approximately 26-28 individuals by name, including couples, household churches, and fellow workers — an extraordinary personal network.'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 3, 'What is significant about Paul mentioning Andronicus and Junia as "of note among the apostles"?', 'They were Jewish believers who were in Christ before Paul, and were notable among the apostles — suggesting the term "apostle" could be used in a broader sense beyond the Twelve', 'They were two of the original Twelve', 'They were Roman governors', 'They were Gentile converts', 'a', 'Romans 16:7 — "Salute Andronicus and Junia, my kinsmen, and my fellowprisoners, who are of note among the apostles, who also were in Christ before me."'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 4, 'What does Paul''s warning about divisive people in verses 17-18 reveal about threats to the church?', 'False teachers serve their own belly (selfish desires), use smooth speech and flattery to deceive the hearts of the simple — doctrinal integrity must be guarded', 'All disagreements are equally dangerous', 'False teaching was not a concern', 'Only apostles face false teachers', 'a', 'Romans 16:17-18 — "Mark them which cause divisions and offences contrary to the doctrine... by good words and fair speeches deceive the hearts of the simple."'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 5, 'How does Romans 16:20 echo Genesis 3:15?', '"The God of peace shall bruise Satan under your feet shortly" alludes to the protoevangelium — the seed of the woman crushing the serpent''s head — applying it to the church''s victory through Christ', 'It quotes Genesis 3:15 directly', 'There is no connection to Genesis', 'It refers to a different serpent', 'a', 'Romans 16:20 — "The God of peace shall bruise Satan under your feet shortly." The verb "bruise" (syntripsei) echoes Genesis 3:15 (LXX), applying the promise of Satan''s defeat to the church.'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 6, 'What does the closing doxology (verses 25-27) say about the "mystery" now revealed?', 'The mystery kept secret since the world began is now made manifest — the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s salvation plan through faith in Jesus Christ, according to the prophetic Scriptures', 'The mystery remains hidden', 'The mystery is about the end times only', 'The mystery is unrelated to the gospel', 'a', 'Romans 16:25-26 — "The mystery, which was kept secret since the world began, But now is made manifest, and by the scriptures of the prophets... made known to all nations for the obedience of faith."'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 7, 'What house churches does Paul reference in this chapter?', 'The church in the house of Priscilla and Aquila (v.5), the household of Aristobulus (v.10), the household of Narcissus (v.11), and the brethren with Asyncritus (v.14) and Philologus (v.15)', 'Only one large central church', 'No house churches are mentioned', 'Three synagogues', 'a', 'Romans 16:5,10,11,14,15 — Multiple house churches are named, showing that early Roman Christianity was a network of small congregations meeting in homes.'),
('Romans', 16, 'adults', 8, 'How does the structure of Romans 16 serve as a window into early church life?', 'It reveals a diverse community: men and women in ministry, Jews and Gentiles together, house churches as the basic unit, travelling missionaries, letter carriers, patronage, and the constant threat of false teaching', 'It shows a rigidly hierarchical institution', 'It reveals a church with no organisation', 'It describes a purely Jewish community', 'a', 'Romans 16 — The greetings, commendation of Phoebe, warnings, and doxology together provide one of the most detailed portraits of the early church''s social structure, diversity, and challenges.');
